{"title_page": "Virginia Episcopal School", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n| name = Virginia Episcopal School\n| logo = School logo of Virginia Episcopal School.jpg\n| logo_size = 150px\n| image = Virginia Episcopal School Jett Hall.jpg\n| image_size = 225px\n| caption = Jett Hall, VES's main building\n| motto = ''\"Toward Full Stature\"''\n| address = 400 VES Road\n| city = [[Lynchburg, Virginia|Lynchburg]]\n| state = [[Virginia]]\n| zipcode = 24503\n| country = [[United States]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|37|27|9.5|N|79|11|26.5|W|display=inline,title}}\n| other_name = VES\n| type = Private, [[College-preparatory school|college preparatory]], [[Boarding school|boarding]] and [[day school]]\n| established = {{Start date and age|1916}}\n| founder = Reverend [[Robert Carter Jett]]\n| religious_affiliation = [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America|Episcopalian]]\n| grades = 9-12\n| head_of_school = G. Thomas Battle, Jr. '83\n| faculty = 40\n| gender = Co-educational\n| enrollment = 260\n| average_class_size = 11\n| ratio = 6:1\n| campus_size = {{Convert|160|acre|km2}}\n| campus_type = [[Suburban]]\n| colors = Garnet and White {{color box|maroon}} {{color box|white}}\n| athletics_conference = Virginia Independent Conference (Boys) <br> Blue Ridge Conference (Girls)\n| team_name = The Fighting Bishops\n| website = {{URL|www.ves.org}}\n| module = {{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Virginia Episcopal School\n  | embed = yes\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | designated_other1 = Virginia Landmarks Register\n  | designated_other1_date = June 17, 1992<ref name=register>{{cite web|title=Virginia Landmarks Register|url=http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/register_counties_cities.htm|publisher=Virginia Department of Historic Resources|accessdate=19 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053819/http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/register_counties_cities.htm|archive-date=21 September 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n  | designated_other1_number = 118-0224\n  | designated_other1_num_position = bottom\n  | image = \n  | caption = \n  | location= 400 Virginia Episcopal School Rd., [[Lynchburg, Virginia]]\n  | locmapin = Virginia#USA\n  | built = {{Start date|1916}}\n  | architect = Brooke, Frederick H.\n  | architecture = Colonial Revival, Georgian Revival\n  | added = October 28, 1992\n  | area = {{convert|160|acre}}\n  | governing_body = Private \n  | refnum = 92001392<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Virginia Episcopal School''' ('''VES''') is a private, co-educational [[College-preparatory school|college preparatory]], [[Boarding school|boarding]] and [[day school]] for students in grades 9 - 12, located in [[Lynchburg, Virginia]], United States. The school was first conceived in 1906 by the Reverend [[Robert Carter Jett]], and opened its doors to students in September 1916. Virginia Episcopal School's {{convert|160|acre|km2|adj=on}} campus is located above the [[James River]] in Lynchburg along the foothills of the [[Blue Ridge Mountains]].\n\n==History==\nVirginia Episcopal School's early benefactor, [[Lady Astor|Viscountess Astor]], the first female member of British Parliament, donated much of the school's initial endowment while visiting her family home, [[Mirador (Greenwood, Virginia)|Mirador]], in [[Albemarle County]].  Lady Astor maintained a keen interest in the school for the rest of her life and was instrumental in having her father [[Chiswell Langhorne]] donate the school chapel in memory of his wife Nancy Witcher Keene (parents of Lady Astor).<ref name=VAnom>{{cite web|url=https://www.dhr.virginia.gov/VLR_to_transfer/PDFNoms/118-0224_Virginia_Episcopal_School_1992_Final_Nomination.pdf|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory/Nomination: Virginia Episcopal School |author=Calder Loth |date=March 1992|publisher=Virginia Department of Historic Resources}} and [http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Lynchburg/VAEpiscopalSchool_photo.htm ''Accompanying photo'']</ref>\n\nVirginia Episcopal School opened its doors to students in September 1916. Jett Hall was completed the same year under the direction of Frederick H. Brooke, a prominent Washington architect. Pendleton Hall was completed in 1918, enabling enrollment to be increased from sixty-three to one-hundred eleven boys. In 1919, Langhorne Memorial Chapel was consecrated. This was followed by the opening of Barksdale Gymnasium in 1920. As bishop of the newly-created Diocese of Southwest Virginia, Bishop Jett would serve ''ex officio'' as chairman of the school's board of trustees until his retirement in 1938.\n\nOriginally all-white, the school was [[Racial integration|racially integrated]] in 1967, when the first two [[African Americans|black]] students entered the school in a successful initiative organized by the Stouffer Foundation, which also arranged the integration of other elite prep schools in the South, including [[Saint Andrew's School (Boca Raton, Florida)|Saint Andrew's School]] in Florida, the [[Asheville School]] in North Carolina, and the [[The Westminster Schools|Westminster School]] in Georgia.<ref>Mosi Secret, [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/07/magazine/the-way-to-survive-it-was-to-make-as.html 'The Way to Survive It Was to Make A's'], ''New York Times Magazine'' (September 7, 2017).</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*Dr. [[Henry C. Bourne Jr.|Henry C. Bourne]], Jr.: President, administrator, and faculty member at the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]].\n*[[Erskine Bowles]]: [[White House Chief of Staff]] under President [[Bill Clinton]],<ref>Todd S. Purdum, [https://www.nytimes.com/1996/11/09/us/a-southern-point-man-erskine-boyce-bowles.html A Southern Point Man: Erskine Boyce Bowles], ''New York Times'' (November 9, 1996).</ref> co-chair of the bipartisan National Commission on Fiscal Responsibility and Reform under President Obama, and tenth Chancellor of the [[University of North Carolina]] public university system.\n*[[Steve Cowper]]: Sixth [[governor of Alaska]].<ref>[http://w3.legis.state.ak.us/100years/bio.php?id=1027 Steve Cowper], ''100 Years of Alaska's Legislature, From Territorial Days to Today'', Alaska Legislature.</ref>\n*[[Hardy Cross Dillard]]: United States judge of the [[International Court of Justice]],<ref>William Bland Whitley, [http://www.lva.virginia.gov/public/dvb/bio.asp?b=Dillard_Hardy_Cross Hardy Cross Dillard], ''[[Dictionary of Virginia Biography]]''.</ref> former Dean of the [[University of Virginia School of Law]].\n*Paul Fulton, Jr.: Former Dean of the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|University of North Carolina's]] [[Kenan-Flagler Business School]]; founder, former chairman of Bassett Furniture Industries, and former President of Sara Lee Corporation.\n*[[William B. Harrison, Jr.]]: Former CEO of [[J.P. Morgan Chase]]<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2002-04-21/resume-william-b-dot-harrison-jr-dot Resume: William B. Harrison Jr]: Bloomberg BusinessWeek (April 21, 2002).</ref>\n*[[Phil Haynes (American football)|Phil Haynes]]: Professional football player for the Seattle Seahawks.\n*[[Vivian Howard]]: Chef, restaurateur, television personality; star of PBS series \u201cA Chef\u2019s Life,\u201d for which she has earned a Daytime Emmy for Outstanding Culinary Program.\n*[[Jerrauld Jones]]: Former member of the Virginia House of Delegates.\n*[[D. Holmes Morton]]: Physician, founder of the Clinic for Special Children in Strasburg, Pennsylvania; 2006 MacArthur Foundation Fellowship \u201cGenius Grant\u201d recipient; recipient of the Albert Schweitzer Prize for Humanitarianism; and one of ''Time'' magazine's \u201cHeroes of Medicine\u201d for his work in genetic illnesses (dropped out, later received honorary degree).<ref>Melissa Hendricks, [http://pages.jh.edu/jhumag/1194web/barndoc.html A Doctor Who Makes Barn Calls], ''Johns Hopkins Magazine'' (November 1994).</ref>\n*[[Paul Taylor (choreographer)|Paul Taylor]]: Modern dance choreographer, received National Merit of Arts from President Clinton, MacArthur Foundation Fellowship \u201cgenius award.\u201d<ref>Sarah Kaufman, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/07/16/AR2010071603883.html A singular vision: Nearing 80, Paul Taylor is as moving a dance figure as ever], ''Washington Post'' (July 18, 2010).</ref>\n*Loretta Pieper: Youngest judge in German history at age 26; founded Webmiles AG internet company and Fine Arts Partners.\n*[[Lee M. Thomas]]: Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency under President Ronald Reagan.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Virginia Episcopal School}}\n* [http://www.ves.org Virginia Episcopal School]\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Virginia}}\n\n[[Category:School buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Private high schools in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Episcopal schools in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1916]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Lynchburg, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Colonial Revival architecture in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Schools in Lynchburg, Virginia]]\n[[Category:1916 establishments in Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n| name = Virginia Episcopal School\n| logo = School logo of Virginia Episcopal School.jpg\n| logo_size = 150px\n| image = Virginia Episcopal School Jett Hall.jpg\n| image_size = 225px\n| caption = Jett Hall, VES's main building\n| motto = ''\"Toward Full Stature\"''\n| address = 400 VES Road\n| city = [[Lynchburg, Virginia|Lynchburg]]\n| state = [[Virginia]]\n| zipcode = 24503\n| country = [[United States]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|37|27|9.5|N|79|11|26.5|W|display=inline,title}}\n| other_name = VES\n| type = Private, [[College-preparatory school|college preparatory]], [[Boarding school|boarding]] and [[day school]]\n| established = {{Start date and age|1916}}\n| founder = Reverend [[Robert Carter